+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the tick engine ‚Äî pattern config, the gate/respawn circle-back, extendRun + run.extended audit entries, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant.
+---
+
+The core tick engine described in
+[How an offload run executes](/pangolin/explanation/how-offload-runs/) is intentionally
+fixed: it processes a DAG you gave it at submit time and nothing more. **Execution
+patterns** are the layer above that engine that lets a run grow safely *while it runs*
+‚Äî a map step fans out to N workers whose count was unknown at submit time, or a gate
+step fails validation and respawns a fix pass before continuing downstream. This page
+explains how patterns work, how you configure them per queue, and what invariants keep
+the graph acyclic and auditable no matter what a pattern emits.
+
+## What an execution pattern is
+
+An execution pattern is a **pure, stateless strategy object** bound to a queue. After
+each engine tick completes its four phases (ready ‚Üí reconcile ‚Üí fire ‚Üí cascade), the
+orchestrator runs a **pattern phase**: for every unsealed run on a pattern-bound queue
+it calls `pattern.onTerminal(terminalItems, currentGraph)` and receives back zero or
+more **spawn directives** ‚Äî descriptions of new WorkItems to add to the run.
+
+Three built-in patterns cover the common shapes of dynamic work:
+
+- **`static-dag`** ‚Äî the default; emits nothing. The graph submitted is the graph that
+  runs. Use this when you know every step at submission time.
+- **`pipeline`** ‚Äî each stage gate can respawn a repair pass. When a gate item
+  terminates `failed`, the pattern emits a corrective step whose `depends_on` points
+  at the failed item and whose downstream is wired forward to the original next stage.
+  The failed branch becomes sealed history; the repair branch becomes the live path.
+- **`map-reduce`** ‚Äî a splitter item runs first and writes the set of shards to
+  `outputs/`; on the splitter's completion the pattern reads those outputs and emits
+  one map worker per shard, then a single reduce item that `depends_on` all map
+  workers. The reduce item does not exist at submit time; it is created by the pattern
+  the tick after the splitter finishes.
+
+Patterns are deliberately kept pure and stateless. They re-derive the same spawn
+directives every time they scan the same terminal items ‚Äî this is what makes them
+crash-safe (see [Replay safety](#replay-safety-by-construction) below).
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are configured in `pangolin.config` at the queue level, not at the run level.
+Every run submitted to that queue inherits the queue's pattern:
+
+```jsonc
+// pangolin.config.ts (excerpt)
+{
+  "orchestrator": {
+    "queues": [
+      {
+        "name": "pipeline-q",
+        "concurrency": 2,
+        "pattern": {
+          "type": "pipeline",
+          "maxRepairPasses": 2
+        }
+      },
+      {
+        "name": "fanout-q",
+        "concurrency": 8,
+        "pattern": {
+          "type": "map-reduce",
+          "splitterItemId": "split",
+          "reduceItemId": "reduce"
+        }
+      }
+    ]
+  }
+}
+```
+
+A queue with no `pattern` key defaults to `static-dag` and behaves exactly like a
+pre-pattern queue ‚Äî no pattern phase runs, no `extendRun` calls are made, and the
+run seals the tick everything goes terminal.
+
+Pattern options are validated at serve startup; an unknown `type` or an inconsistent
+option set (e.g. `map-reduce` without a `splitterItemId`) is a hard startup error, not
+a runtime one. This surfaces misconfiguration before any work is dispatched.
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+The most important pattern behaviour ‚Äî and the one most likely to surprise ‚Äî is the
+**gate/respawn circle-back** in the `pipeline` pattern.
+
+A *gate* item is a validation step that sits between two stages of a pipeline. If it
+succeeds, dependents proceed normally. If it fails, the pipeline does not stop: the
+pattern emits a *respawn* ‚Äî a repair item that targets the same resource the gate just
+validated ‚Äî and then a *retry gate* that runs after the repair and wires back into the
+original downstream stage.
+
+Crucially, this is **not** a cycle in the graph. The failed gate item stays in the
+graph as a terminal `failed` node. The repair item's `depends_on` points *backward* at
+the failed gate (which is already terminal ‚Äî it will never be re-executed), and the
+retry gate's `depends_on` points at the repair. The original downstream stage's
+`depends_on` is amended to accept either the original gate *or* the retry gate as its
+predecessor. The graph grows forward; the failed subtree is permanently sealed as
+history.
+
+```
+submit-time graph:
+
+  fetch ‚Üí lint-gate ‚Üí deploy
+
+after lint-gate fails, pattern emits two new items:
+
+  fetch ‚Üí lint-gate(failed) ‚Üí repair-lint ‚Üí lint-gate-retry ‚Üí deploy
+                           ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ (repair-lint depends_on lint-gate) ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îò
+```
+
+From the engine's perspective there is nothing special here: `repair-lint` and
+`lint-gate-retry` are ordinary WorkItems added via `extendRun`, with ordinary
+`depends_on` edges. The pattern is only responsible for computing *what* to add; the
+engine handles scheduling, locking, and retry exactly as for any other item.
+
+`maxRepairPasses` (default `1`) caps how many times this circle-back may fire per
+original gate. When the cap is reached and the latest retry gate still fails, the
+pattern emits nothing ‚Äî the gate is terminally failed, its transitive dependents
+cascade to `skipped`, and the run settles.
+
+## extendRun and run.extended audit entries
+
+Spawn directives are applied through a single audited seam: **`extendRun`**.
+
+`extendRun` does exactly what `submitRun` does on initial submission, for the
+incremental case:
+
+1. Validates the new items against the *merged* graph (existing items plus the
+   additions) using the same `validateRun` function used at submit time ‚Äî no cycles,
+   no dangling `depends_on` references, no duplicate ids.
+2. Inserts the new items into the run-state store in `pending` status.
+3. Writes a **`run.extended`** audit entry that names the actor (`pattern:<queueName>`),
+   the cause item (the terminal item that triggered the spawn), and the ids of every
+   newly added item.
+
+Because `extendRun` runs inside the same tick as the pattern phase, and the seal check
+runs *after* the pattern phase, a run that just grew structurally cannot seal that
+tick ‚Äî the new `pending` items prevent it. This is the correct ordering: seal-then-check
+would produce an audit gap between when items exist and when they appear in the log.
+
+The `run.extended` entry is what lets `pangolin verify` cover dynamically grown graphs.
+The verifier reads the audit log in sequence, applying `submitRun` entries and
+`run.extended` entries in order, and reconstructs the full graph as it existed at each
+point in time. The closure check ‚Äî every consumed artifact is produced by a known item
+‚Äî holds over the dynamically grown graph with no additional verifier code, because the
+graph is reconstructed from the audit log rather than re-derived.
+
+## Replay safety by construction
+
+Patterns keep no mutable state between calls. Every call to `onTerminal` receives the
+full set of current terminal items and the current graph, and re-derives its spawn
+directives from scratch. Spawn item ids are **deterministic** ‚Äî computed from the cause
+item id and the pass number, not from a counter or timestamp ‚Äî so running `onTerminal`
+twice on the same inputs produces the same ids.
+
+`extendRun` enforces idempotency at the store level: any id already present in the run
+is silently skipped. Together these two properties mean that a crash between the pattern
+phase and the seal check, followed by a restart and re-scan, re-derives exactly the
+same directives and `extendRun` absorbs them as a no-op. No dedup logic is needed
+beyond what the store already provides for initial submission.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+All spawn directives must satisfy one hard invariant: **every edge in a spawned item's
+`depends_on` must point at an item that already exists in the graph, and no spawned
+item may be the `depends_on` target of any item that already exists.**
+
+In plain terms: new items may depend on old items, but old items may not depend on new
+items. The graph grows by **appending leaves** (and internal nodes whose `depends_on`
+is entirely backward-pointing), never by inserting nodes into the middle of existing
+dependency chains ‚Äî and never by adding edges that point forward into the not-yet-run
+portion of the graph.
+
+`extendRun`'s `validateRun` call enforces this structurally: after merging the new
+items into the existing graph it runs a topological sort and rejects any cycle. Because
+existing items already have their `depends_on` edges ‚Äî which cannot be modified after
+submission ‚Äî any new item that tries to make an existing item depend on it would have
+to add an edge to an existing item's record, which `extendRun` does not do. The only
+edges that can reference new items are edges *from* new items.
+
+This invariant has three practical consequences:
+
+- **Settled history stays settled.** A terminal item is terminal forever. A pattern
+  cannot "re-open" a completed step by inserting a dependency on it from an earlier
+  point in the graph. The audit log's past is immutable.
+- **The engine needs no special handling for dynamic runs.** The tick loop processes
+  the graph it sees at each tick. New items are pending when they arrive; they ready
+  when their (backward-pointing) `depends_on` complete; they fire, reconcile, and
+  terminate exactly like submit-time items. No tick-loop code was modified to
+  support patterns.
+- **`pangolin verify` terminates.** Because the graph is always acyclic, the topological
+  walk the verifier uses to check provenance closure always terminates and always
+  produces a unique ordering. A dynamic run is not a special case for verification;
+  it is just a larger acyclic graph.
